  "datePublished": "2026-03-18",
  "description": "A Locale is a complete Heyting algebra treated as a space defined by its lattice of observable opens — a pointfree topological space. The defining move (Isbell 1972): a space can be constituted entirely by what is observable within it, without any prior set of points. A locale is a frame (complete distributive lattice) viewed as a space; its morphisms are frame homomorphisms running in the opposite direction. By Johnstone's nucleus-sublocale theorem (Stone Spaces, Theorem II.2.3), every nucleus on a locale corresponds to a unique sublocale, and the lattice of sublocales is a coframe anti-isomorphic to the lattice of nuclei.",
  "name": "Locale",
